Mouthparts (
Fig. 4
) typical of the genus.

(i) presence of an up-turned rostral tip in
O. maui
(versus not up-turned tip in
O. balssi
). (ii) distolateral tooth of proximal segment of antennular peduncle longer, exceeding half intermediate segment length (versus less than half in
O. balssi
). (iii) distolateral tooth of scaphocerite longer, more robust, about 0.165 of scaphocerite (versus 0.14 in
O. balssi
). (iv) endite of maxilla.

Endite of maxilla slender (versus broad in 

O. balssi

). (v) third ambulatory pereiopod dactyl with accessory tooth feebly bidentate, distal tooth blunt (versus strongly acutely bidentate in 

O. balssi

); ventral denticles anteroverted (versus erect in 

O. balssi

). (vi) Sixth abdominal somite with posterolateral and posteroventral angles more acute (versus less acute in 

O. balssi

).

Colouration. Female (
Fig. 9
) generally translucent with whole body densely covered with small white spots, appendages colourless, ovary pale green, cornea white. Male (
Fig. 10
) generally translucent, with sparse scattered small white dots over body.
